<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="comprehensure.DASHBOARD.StoryPage.StoryPage2"  
             BackgroundColor="#F4F8FB"
             Shell.NavBarIsVisible="False">

    <Grid RowDefinitions="Auto, *, Auto">

        <Border Grid.Row="0" BackgroundColor="#80c2ed" StrokeThickness="0" Margin="0,-10,0,0" HeightRequest="160">
            <Border.StrokeShape>
                <RoundRectangle CornerRadius="0,0,50,50" />
            </Border.StrokeShape>
            <VerticalStackLayout VerticalOptions="Center" Margin="0,10,0,0">
                <Label Text="The Clockmaker’s Secret" FontSize="28" FontAttributes="Bold" 
                       TextColor="#1B3A57" HorizontalOptions="Center" />
                <Label Text="Module 02: Full Story" FontSize="14" TextColor="#1B3A57" 
                       HorizontalOptions="Center" Opacity="0.8"/>
            </VerticalStackLayout>
        </Border>

        <CarouselView Grid.Row="1" x:Name="StoryCarousel" Margin="0,20"
                      IndicatorView="indicatorView" PeekAreaInsets="30">
            <CarouselView.ItemsSource>
                <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
                    <x:String>In the quiet town of Maplewood, a narrow street was lined with small shops that had stood for many years. Between a warm bakery that smelled of fresh bread and a cozy bookstore filled with novels stood an old clock shop with a wooden sign that read, Alden’s Timepieces.</x:String>
                    <x:String>The gold paint on the letters had faded, and the windows were slightly fogged from years of dust and oil, yet the shop remained open every day without fail. Inside worked Mr. Alden, the town’s clockmaker. He was an elderly man with silver hair and round glasses.</x:String>
                    <x:String>His hands were steady and careful, even after decades of repairing tiny gears and springs. The shop was always filled with the steady ticking of clocks. Tall grandfather clocks stood proudly, small pocket watches rested in cases, and cuckoo clocks hung near the ceiling.</x:String>
                    <x:String>Though each clock was different, they somehow ticked in perfect harmony, creating a calm rhythm. People respected Mr. Alden because of his unusual way of selling clocks. Whenever a customer pointed to a clock, he rarely handed it to them right away.</x:String>
                    <x:String>Instead, he would ask questions about their lives—when they woke up, how they spent afternoons, and if they liked quiet while working. After listening, he would suggest a different clock—one that seemed to fit them better. Most found this strange, but he was always right.</x:String>
                    <x:String>One rainy afternoon, Clara stepped into the shop. She was preparing for exams and wanted a small clock for her desk to help manage her time. Her eyes landed on a simple silver clock. It was modern, neat, and quiet. She decided it would be perfect.</x:String>
                    <x:String>“I would like this one, please,” Clara said. Mr. Alden studied her expression, noticing the tension in her shoulders. He walked toward a shelf at the back and picked up a wooden clock. Its face had a strange design carved into it—a maze made of thin winding lines.</x:String>
                    <x:String>“This clock would suit you better,” he said gently. He explained that the clock was not just for telling time; it would teach patience, attention, and observation. Clara did not fully understand, but something about his calm voice made her trust him. She bought the wooden clock.</x:String>
                    <x:String>That evening, she placed the clock on her desk. As she reviewed her notes, she noticed something different. Every hour, a small hand inside moved along the carved maze instead of circling the edge. It followed the winding path carefully and paused at certain points.</x:String>
                    <x:String>Clara began to draw the path in her notebook. Over the next few days, she continued observing the movement. She noticed patterns in where the hand paused. Some of the stopping points formed shapes that looked like letters; others seemed to represent numbers.</x:String>
                    <x:String>Clara realized that the maze was forming hidden messages. The first encouraged her to observe closely. Another appeared later, reminding her to find patterns and pay attention to details. The clock was giving her small puzzles that required careful thinking.</x:String>
                    <x:String>As weeks passed, Clara became more patient. She no longer rushed through work. She read each question slowly, double-checked her answers, and thought about problems step by step. Even outside of studies, she noticed simple patterns in daily life and rhythms of the street.</x:String>
                    <x:String>The clock quietly trained her mind. It reminded her that clear thinking requires focus and patience. By the end of the month, she felt more confident and was thinking more clearly. She returned to Mr. Alden’s shop to thank him. He smiled and said she had learned well.</x:String>
                    <x:String>Mr. Alden explained that the lessons were never only in the clock, but in the patience and curiosity she chose to keep. Clara left feeling grateful, realizing she carried a new way of thinking. She understood that time is not only something to measure, but something to use wisely.</x:String>
                </x:Array>
            </CarouselView.ItemsSource>

            <CarouselView.ItemTemplate>
                <DataTemplate>
                    <Grid HorizontalOptions="Center" WidthRequest="700" VerticalOptions="Center">
                        <Border BackgroundColor="#BDE0FE" Rotation="-2" HeightRequest="450" TranslationY="8" StrokeThickness="0">
                            <Border.StrokeShape>
                                <RoundRectangle CornerRadius="30"/>
                            </Border.StrokeShape>
                        </Border>
                        <Border BackgroundColor="#FFF9C4" Padding="40" StrokeThickness="0" HeightRequest="450">
                            <Border.StrokeShape>
                                <RoundRectangle CornerRadius="30"/>
                            </Border.StrokeShape>
                            <Border.Shadow>
                                <Shadow Brush="#D4C463" Offset="0,10" Radius="20" Opacity="0.3"/>
                            </Border.Shadow>
                            <ScrollView>
                                <Label Text="{Binding .}" FontSize="20" LineHeight="1.5" TextColor="#1B3A57" 
                                       HorizontalTextAlignment="Center" VerticalTextAlignment="Center" FontFamily="Calibri" />
                            </ScrollView>
                        </Border>
                    </Grid>
                </DataTemplate>
            </CarouselView.ItemTemplate>
        </CarouselView>

        <VerticalStackLayout Grid.Row="2" Spacing="10" Padding="0,0,0,30">
            <HorizontalStackLayout HorizontalOptions="Center" Spacing="5" Margin="0,0,0,5">
                <Label Text="Slide " TextColor="Gray" FontSize="12" />
                <Label Text="{Binding Source={x:Reference StoryCarousel}, Path=Position}" 
                       TextColor="#1B3A57" FontAttributes="Bold" FontSize="12" />
                <Label Text=" of 14" TextColor="Gray" FontSize="12" />
            </HorizontalStackLayout>

            <IndicatorView x:Name="indicatorView" IndicatorColor="#BDE0FE" SelectedIndicatorColor="#1B3A57" HorizontalOptions="Center" />

            <Button Text="GO TO QUIZ" BackgroundColor="#1B3A57" TextColor="White" FontAttributes="Bold" FontSize="18" 
                    CornerRadius="30" HeightRequest="60" WidthRequest="250" HorizontalOptions="Center" Margin="0,10,0,0"
                    Clicked="OnGoToQuizClicked" />
        </VerticalStackLayout>
    </Grid>
</ContentPage>